{{Infobox media | name = CV-2000 | logo = | image = | caption = | type = [[Magnetic Tape]] | encoding = 525-lines/60Hz and 625-lines/50Hz (not [[PAL]] or [[NTSC]] as monochrome-only format) | created = 1965 | capacity = | read = [[Helical scan]] | write = [[Helical scan]] | standard = [[Interlaced video]] | owner = [[Sony]] | use = [[Home movies]] | dimensions= | extended from = | extended to = }}
'''CV-2000''' was one of the world's first home [[video tape recorder]]s (VTR), introduced by [[Sony]] in August, 1965.<ref name="popular_mechanics">{{cite web |url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/technology/gadgets/a2726/4255160/ |title=The 10 Video Formats HD DVD Will Meet in Heaven |accessdate=2008-03-25 |last=Derene |first=Glenn |date=2008-03-20 |publisher=[[Popular Mechanics]] }}</ref> The 'CV' in the model name stood for 'Consumer Video'. This was Sony's domestic format throughout the 1960s.<ref name="LabGuy">{{cite web |url=http://www.labguysworld.com/Sony_CV-2000D.htm |title=Sony CV-2000D First Consumer Videocorder |accessdate=2008-03-27 |date=2005-01-09 |publisher=LabGuy's World }}</ref><ref>[http://www.sony.net/Fun/design/history/product/1960/cv-2000.html Sony.com History]</ref>
The CV-2000 was developed by Sony engineer [[Nobutoshi Kihara]]. On its release, each machine cost US$695. It used {{convert|1/2|in|mm|adj=mid|-wide}} [[video tape]] in a [[reel-to-reel]] format, meaning the tape had to be manually threaded around the [[helical scan]] video head drum. The CV-2000 was one-tenth the weight and price of other [[analog video]] recording products of its era.<ref name="EETimes">{{cite web |url=http://www.eetimes.com/special/special_issues/millennium/companies/sony.html |title=Sony: electronics ordered 'to go' |accessdate=2008-03-25 |last=Hara |first=Yoshiko |publisher=[[Electronic Engineering Times|EETimes]] }}</ref> It recorded television programs in [[Black-and-white|black and white]] using the [[skip field]] process, which produced a maximum 200-lines resolution. The tape moved at a speed of 7.5&nbsp;inches per second.<ref name="Retro_Thing">{{cite web |url=http://www.retrothing.com/2005/11/the_sony_cv2000.html |title=The Sony CV-2000 Reel-to-Reel Video Recorder |accessdate=2008-03-27 |date=November 2005 |publisher=Retro Thing }}</ref> Each reel of video tape cost US$40, and could hold one hour of video. Although CV-2000 was aimed at the home market, it was mainly used in business and educational institutions.<ref name="popular_mechanics"/>
Ten models were developed in the CV series: CV-2000, TCV-2010, TCV-2020, CV-2100, TCV-2110, TCV-2120, CV-2200, DV-2400, CV-2600 and CV-5100.<ref name="LabGuy"/> Sony also sold an optional 'Video Camera Ensemble', known as the VCK-2000. This add-on kit contained a separate video camera, a microphone, and a tripod.<ref name="Retro_Thing"/>
One of its shortcomings as a format was the omission of the ability to adjust [[Video tape tracking|tracking]], which made interchangeability of tapes between different machines almost impossible. Sony's later AV series machines included this feature.<ref>[http://www.smecc.org/sony_cv_series_video.htm smecc.org] Sony CV series video</ref> The CV video recorders fell into disuse with the arrival of the [[EIAJ-1|EIAJ type 1]] standard that was used by many companies, including Sony with their AV series machines.
